href="ericczhao.xml"
addr="ericczhao"
title="Eric Zhao">Eric Zhao</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>I was surprised to find it possible to properly type (though not directly via Rime) and render the character 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="zh-hant">𰻞</html:span>

 (<fr:em>bíang</fr:em>) when recording <fr:link
type="local"
href="zzhaoe-000X.xml"
addr="zzhaoe-000X"
title="
  
  𰻞𰻞麵

">a recipe for 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="zh-hant">𰻞𰻞麵</html:span>

</fr:link> from my dad, since I was, for whatever reason, under the impression that it wasn't part of Unicode. Apparently, it was added in 2020 in <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://blog.unicode.org/2020/03/announcing-unicode-standard-version-130.html">Unicode 13.0</fr:link> as one of the codepoints (precisely, <fr:code>U+30EDE</fr:code>; there's also 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="zh-hans">𰻝</html:span>

 as <fr:code>U+30EDD</fr:code>) in CJK Unified Ideographs Extension G, the first block of the Tertiary Ideographic Plane.</fr:p><fr:p>This block also includes 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">𱁬</html:span>

 (<fr:em>taito</fr:em>; <fr:em>daito</fr:em>; <fr:em>otodo</fr:em>; <fr:code>U+3106C</fr:code>), an 84-stroke behemoth made by sticking 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">䨺</html:span>

 (<fr:em>tai</fr:em>; <fr:code>U+4A3A</fr:code>; itself three clouds 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">雲</html:span>

 together, meaning "cloudy") and 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">龘</html:span>

 (<fr:em>tou</fr:em>; <fr:code>U+9F98</fr:code>; three dragons 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">龍</html:span>

, meant to resemble a dragon flying or climbing). It's a Japanese-coined character, or <fr:em>kokuji</fr:em> (
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">国字</html:span>

), but the origins are fairly uncertain. In the early 1960s, a man showed a namecard with this surname to the staff of a brokerage office... or so it goes according to the 1981 <fr:link
type="local"
href="niwa-seishi-no-gogen.xml"
addr="niwa-seishi-no-gogen"
title="
  
  姓氏の語源

">
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">姓氏の語源</html:span>

</fr:link>, an etymological dictionary of surnames. Some scholars think it's an erroneous ghost letter. 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">䨺龘</html:span>

, written separately, was perhaps an alias. In any case, it's now the name of a <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://seg2017.com/otodo/">series of ramen shops</fr:link> starting in Kita-Matsudo (
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">北松戸</html:span>

) in Chiba. I think I'd like to go there sometime.</fr:p><fr:p>It seems like some netizens have borrowed the character into Chinese, developing humorous neologisms like 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="zh-hant">𱁬𪚥</html:span>

 (<fr:em>tài zhé</fr:em>; the latter character meaning "verbose"), meaning something like "excessively complicated (of a Chinese character)". One has to zoom in 200% to make anything of it.</fr:p><fr:p>In Chinese, there's also 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="zh-hant">䲜</html:span>

 ("abundance of fish"; <fr:code>U+4C9C</fr:code>) and 
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="zh-hant">䨻</html:span>

 ("roar of thunder"; <fr:code>U+4A3B</fr:code>). In Japanese, there's <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://ksbookshelf.com/nozomu-oohara/WaseikanjiJiten/WaseikanjiJiten_81.html">
  
  <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
lang="ja">𰽔</html:span>

</fr:link> (<fr:em>kagami</fr:em>; <fr:code>U+30F54</fr:code>), which seems to me like a bewildering room of many mirrors. Maybe the folks working on the Noto CJK fonts will get to it one day.</fr:p><fr:p>Here are some new characters I'd like to propose, to further enrich the space of overly dense and illegible ideographs and make the Unicode people very sad:</fr:p>
  

